{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8689420a-e83c-471f-adb5-252a17dc1801","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process ID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` to avoid unbounded trace sizes.\n- `createdump` or `dotnet-dump` are better if the issue is a CPU *spike* you want to snapshot rather than profile over time.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7a608d70-d2e9-4a61-b56e-915a037966f5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"418F:303A77:7C6523E:882AA16:69F15F06"},"id":"bffa5bad-1adf-4f75-b998-832c77c3b1da","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:29:56.251Z","parentId":"f56e0546-457f-486b-99d7-243df1c7d534"}
